snippet.textDisplay:
RICO (the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act) is not as commonly used or even applicable, as many may be led to believe. Racketeering at its inception referred to repeat- or circular schemes of extortion, but its understood legal reference today is much broader.

The core concept of applying the RICO act, is to enable law enforcement to take down criminal and corrupt organizations, companies etc, by charging _everyone_ in it with the crimes committed by _any_ of its members. This tool is particularly useful for taking down high-ups and leaders in such organizations, which is almost always extremely difficult by traditional means - because of technical and personell layers of obfuscation and separation, making it incredibly difficult to pin a serious crime to them directly. By using RICO, they cast a _very_ wide, tight and heavy net over the entire operation, usually creating too many pressure points for the organization to be able to counteract with threats, intimidation, bribery/corruption, violence etc. And by the time any word of the current law enforcement strategy (building an actual RICO case) leaks out or is publicised, investigators and DAs have usually been surveilling, gathering evidence and extensive signed/recorded witness statements, and built strong cases for a big volume of crimes committed by multiple members of the organization, for _years_ already. So when law enforcement make their big raid(s), it's too late for the organization to make any major impact through intimidation of or violence against witnesses and other key actors.
